# W1': a `|>` chain directly after a value-position js` literal NESTED inside
# a larger Go expression in a `{ }` interpolation (`wrap(js`…` |> minify)`).
# Contrast a pipe at the INTERP'S OWN top-level seed (`{ js`…` |> minify }`),
# which parsePipe already strips into a normal pipe Stage and is unaffected —
# this case only fires once the literal is buried inside a call argument, past
# parsePipe's own top-level split. Caught here, at parse time (a pre-check
# mirroring scanGoParts's PipeOff, run before analyze.go's deferred
# SplitGoExprElements split even exists), so the diagnostic wins over the
# later, generic skeleton parse failure the same broken text would otherwise
# hit. No filter package or `wrap` definition is needed: the rejection is
# purely syntactic, before any name resolves.
-- input.gsx --
package demo

component Page() {
	<div>{ wrap(js`f()` |> minify) }</div>
}
-- invoke --
Page()
-- diagnostics.golden --
4:22: whole-literal pipelines are not supported in Go-expression position; wrap the literal in a function call instead
-- render.golden --
